          "content": "# Campaign Spend Trend & Business Impact — Xnurta AI BU3A-CHY 床单-压花/竹纤维/深笠高 SB 精准 sheets+QU\n\n## Campaign under analysis\nThe campaign name in the question (`BU3A-CHY【床单-压花/竹纤维/深笠高】SB精准-sheets+QU词根-商品集-旗舰店@@SB-US000253GQU`) matches exactly one campaign in the account, carrying the `Xnurta AI` management prefix:\n**Xnurta AI BU3A-CHY【床单-压花/竹纤维/深笠高】SB精准-sheets+QU词根-商品集-旗舰店@@SB-US000253GQU** (campaign ID `432062328693014`, SB 精准).\n\n## Data window\nTwo complementary views are available:\n\n- **Long-range** (March 2025 → May 2026, three multi-month buckets): total spend and sales by 4-month period.\n- **Daily** granularity for **2026-02-01 → 2026-05-07** (96 days → 15 weeks, last week partial), which is the right resolution to see \"does spend translate to growth?\".\n\n## Lifetime totals (combining the three multi-month periods)\n\n| Period | Days | Spend | Sales | ACOS | CTR | CVR | CPC | NTB sales |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| 2025-03-05 → 2025-06-30 | 118 | $20,703 | $49,118 | 42% | 1.10% | 18.4% | $2.35 | $32,152 (65%) |\n| 2025-07-01 → 2025-10-31 | 123 | $127,766 | $296,692 | 43% | 4.20% | 21.7% | $2.75 | $206,673 (70%) |\n| 2025-11-01 → 2026-05-07 | 188 | $130,555 | $313,632 | 42% | 4.86% | 25.5% | $2.96 | $231,572 (74%) |\n| **Total / blended** | **429** | **$279,024** | **$659,442** | **42%** | — | — | **$2.81** | **$470,397 (71%)** |\n\n## Weekly trend (2026-02 → 2026-05, the most recent 15 weeks)\n\n| Week | Days | Spend | Sales | ACOS | CPC | CVR | CTR | NTB sales share |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| 2026-W05 | 1 | $597 | $1,692 | 35% | $2.74 | 27.5% | 6.54% | 72% |\n| 2026-W06 | 7 | $5,735 | $15,295 | 37% | $2.77 | 24.1% | 6.13% | 74% |\n| 2026-W07 | 7 | $7,601 | $20,572 | 37% | $2.97 | 31.7% | 7.89% | 72% |\n| 2026-W08 | 7 | $6,658 | $15,009 | **44%** | $3.01 | 23.8% | 4.82% | 77% |\n| 2026-W09 | 7 | $5,250 | $12,190 | **43%** | $3.12 | 24.9% | 4.94% | 73% |\n| 2026-W10 | 7 | $5,177 | $14,017 | 37% | $2.98 | 24.0% | 5.52% | 77% |\n| 2026-W11 | 7 | $6,103 | $15,581 | 39% | $2.91 | 31.7% | 7.62% | 71% |\n| 2026-W12 | 7 | $6,734 | $17,488 | 39% | $2.99 | 31.0% | 8.14% | 74% |\n| 2026-W13 | 7 | $6,155 | $14,982 | 41% | $3.02 | 26.3% | 4.46% | 76% |\n| 2026-W14 | 7 | $5,788 | $13,351 | **43%** | $3.00 | 25.3% | 4.64% | 75% |\n| 2026-W15 | 7 | $6,052 | $15,069 | 40% | $3.00 | 23.6% | 5.72% | 79% |\n| 2026-W16 | 7 | $6,712 | $17,920 | 37% | $2.92 | 31.5% | 8.59% | 74% |\n| 2026-W17 | 7 | $6,330 | $17,751 | 36% | $2.92 | 32.1% | 6.75% | 75% |\n| 2026-W18 | 7 | $5,498 | $11,425 | **48%** | $2.95 | 21.4% | 4.55% | 72% |\n| 2026-W19 | 4 | $3,111 | $5,822 | **53%** | $3.02 | 21.1% | 5.35% | 77% |\n\n## Did the spend translate to business growth?\n\n### Spend trend\nWeekly spend has been remarkably stable at **$5.2K–$7.6K** for the last 15 weeks (coefficient of variation ~11%). This is not a campaign where budget has been deliberately ramped; it is being fed a consistent weekly envelope.\n\nLooking across the longer multi-month buckets: daily spend went from **$175/day** (Mar–Jun 2025) → **$1,039/day** (Jul–Oct 2025) → **$694/day** (Nov 2025 – May 2026). The big scale-up happened in the summer 2025 launch window, then settled at ~$700/day.\n\n### Did the spend produce growth? Yes, in two senses:\n1. **Absolute output per dollar has held steady.** ROAS is ~2.35× across all three multi-month periods (ACOS stuck at 42–43% for 429 days). The campaign is a reliable sales engine, not a degrading one.\n2. **NTB (new-to-brand) sales share *increased*** with scale: 65% → 70% → 74% of revenue is now NTB. That is the real business growth — this campaign is still bringing in net-new customers at rate increasing with tenure, not just re-hitting existing ones.\n\n### But there are warning signs in the last 6 weeks:\n- **W18 and W19 ACOS jumped to 48% and 53%** (vs. the 15-week baseline of 40%).\n- CVR dropped from 31% in W17 to 21% in W18–W19.\n- Weekly sales dropped from ~$18K (W17) to $11.4K (W18) and annualizing ~$20K/wk in W19.\n\nThis is a recent decay signal — not enough weeks to call it a trend, but enough to escalate. Three plausible drivers:\n- SB creative fatigue on the custom image/headline (CTR dropped from 6.8% in W17 to 4.5% in W18, then 5.4% in W19).\n- Competitor CPC pressure (CPC sat at $3.00 from W08 onward, so not the driver — this is a CVR-side collapse).\n- Landing-page or product-detail issue specific to the 旗舰店 page linked from this SB.\n\n## Bottom line\n- **Spend has been stable** at ~$700/day across the last 6 months.\n- **Sales have scaled linearly with spend** (ROAS 2.35×, stable).\n- **NTB share has improved** from 65% → 74% — real business expansion.\n- **W18–W19 show a 15-percentage-point ACOS deterioration** with a CVR collapse; this is recent and should be investigated fast.\n\n## Recommendations\n1. **Audit the SB creative / landing page for W18–W19.** A creative refresh (new image, new headline) typically brings CVR back to trend on SB.\n2. **Don't cut this campaign.** 74% NTB share is a rare find; even at 42–48% ACOS the blended customer-lifetime economics are attractive. Bid down 10–15% *after* the creative refresh, not before.\n3. **Add a second SB Video variant for the same ASIN set** to share the load if creative fatigue is confirmed.\n\n## What I still don't have\n- Placement-level breakdown for this campaign (top-of-search vs product-pages) — would confirm whether ACOS erosion is placement-concentrated.\n- Search-term-level report for this SB — the \"sheets+QU 词根\" targeting set may be matching to a few queries that are now pricing up.\n- Custom image / video creative changes timeline — to verify if a creative swap aligns with the W17 → W18 drop.\n- Competitor CPM trend on the same terms.\n- Absolute NTB *counts* (we have NTB sales and NTB purchases in the daily report, so this is computable but was not the focus above).\n"
