          "content": "# B0D41ZMDPD — Why Have Sales Declined Recently?\n\n## Data window & scope\n- Window: **2026-03-09 → 2026-05-07 (~60 days)**.\n- ASIN **B0D41ZMDPD** — Fanttik / MAS-Tools brand (based on the report metadata; top campaigns target \"T1 MAX solder\"-related queries).\n- Data sources: product × campaign × date report, campaign-level report.\n\n## Weekly trend (based on daily records for this ASIN)\n\n| ISO Week | Days in data | Sales | Orders | **Sales/day** |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| 2026-W11 (Mar 9–15) | 2 | $336 | 5 | **$168** |\n| 2026-W12 (Mar 16–22) | 2 | $246 | 3 | $123 |\n| 2026-W13 (Mar 23–29) | 5 | $557 | 8 | $111 |\n| 2026-W14 (Mar 30–Apr 5) | 2 | $218 | 4 | $109 |\n| 2026-W15 (Apr 6–12) | 4 | $337 | 6 | **$84** |\n| 2026-W16 (Apr 13–19) | 2 | $117 | 2 | **$58** |\n| 2026-W17 (Apr 20–26) | 5 | $350 | 5 | $70 |\n| 2026-W18 (Apr 27–May 3) | 5 | $560 | 10 | $112 |\n| 2026-W19 (May 4–7) | 2 | $224 | 4 | $112 |\n\n**Pattern**: from W11's baseline ($168/day) to W16's trough ($58/day) — a **~65% decline over 5 weeks**. Partial recovery in W17–W19 (back to ~$112/day) but still short of the W11 peak.\n\nThese are **ad-attributed** daily sales from records where start == end date in the data. The daily coverage is sparse (2–5 days per week captured at daily granularity), so weekly numbers here are best read as relative changes, not absolute totals.\n\n## Total ad sales for this ASIN in the window\n- **Ad-attributed sales**: $234,300\n- **Combined estimated ad spend**: ~$35K (derived from campaign-level spend apportioned by ASIN share of campaign sales)\n- **Implied ASIN ad-ACOS**: ~15%\n\n## Top 10 campaigns driving this ASIN's sales\n\n| Campaign | ASIN sales | Est. spend | Est. ACOS |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Xnurta AI SP-T1 MAX-KW-A-solder | $72,180 | $16,708 | 23% |\n| Xnurta AI SP-T1 MAX-Brands-solder | $29,870 | $3,522 | **12%** |\n| Xnurta AI SP-T1 MAX-KW-B-solder | $27,395 | $6,332 | 23% |\n| Xnurta AI SP-KW-T1 MAX-AMC-solder | $27,332 | $3,831 | **14%** |\n| Xnurta AI SP-T1 MAX-CAT-solder | $12,450 | $2,484 | 20% |\n| Xnurta AI SB-F2 Master RT-KW-Brand-VCPM-1.30 | $6,234 | $679 | 11% |\n| Xnurta AI SP-F2 Master RT-KW-Brand | $2,865 | $135 | 5% |\n| Xnurta AI SP-E2 ULTRA-BRAND-screwdriver | $2,720 | $402 | 15% |\n| Xnurta AI SP-F2 Pro RT-KW-Brand | $2,520 | $110 | 4% |\n| Xnurta AI SBV-T1 MAX-KW-横版-solder | $1,828 | $990 | **54%** |\n\n### Readings\n- The ASIN is overwhelmingly driven by the \"T1 MAX solder\" keyword cluster (top 5 campaigns, all labeled \"SP-T1 MAX...-solder\", generate $169K of the $234K total = 72%).\n- ACOS structure is fine: KW-A/B at 23%, brand word at 5–12%, only the SBV campaign is underperforming at 54%.\n\n## Why did sales decline?\n\nFour candidate explanations, ranked by evidence in this data:\n\n### 1. Most likely — seasonality/category demand drop in the T1 MAX solder SKU\n- Weekly sales/day went from $168 in W11 to $58 in W16. This is not a gradual bid drift — it's a sharp demand drop.\n- The partial recovery in W18 (back to $112) while ad spend mix hasn't changed (campaigns stable) points to external demand shift, not an internal campaign problem.\n- **Solder / soldering station** is a category that sees sharp demand cycles around holiday gift periods; a late-March/early-April drop after a February gifting window is consistent with this.\n\n### 2. Possible — ad ACOS ceiling reducing impression share on \"KW-A-solder\"\n- KW-A-solder consumes $16.7K of spend at 23% ACOS. If Xnurta AI's target ACOS was lowered to 20% in mid-April, the bidder would have pulled back, reducing impressions and sales.\n- **Cannot confirm without the Xnurta AI target-ACOS changelog** — flagged below.\n\n### 3. Possible — SBV campaign is noise\n- SBV-T1 MAX (54% ACOS, $990 spend) is converting poorly and probably shouldn't be running. It's a small contributor but a leaky one.\n\n### 4. Less likely — listing / inventory issue\n- No signal in this data (detailPageViews = 0 in all rows, so can't confirm organic traffic changes).\n- Would need inventory snapshot / Buy Box rate to rule in/out.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n1. **Check seller-central listing status for B0D41ZMDPD**: Buy Box percent, stock level, review rating and count over the last 60 days. If any of these moved in mid-April, that's the story — not ads.\n2. **Check Xnurta AI target-ACOS setting for the SP-T1 MAX-KW-A-solder campaign**. If it was tightened in mid-April, relaxing it from \"target 20%\" back to \"target 23%\" would restore volume at the ACOS the ASIN has always supported.\n3. **Pause the SBV-T1 MAX-横版 campaign** (54% ACOS). Small gain, but clean.\n4. **Check for competitor price changes on the 'T1 MAX' product category**. If a competitor cut price in early April, the CVR drop will show up as reduced sales despite unchanged ad targeting.\n5. **Extend the data window**: pull last 90 days to see if W11 was itself an anomaly high point. A $168/day baseline in a newer SKU could be promotional lift, and $112/day is the real baseline.\n\n## What I still don't have\n\n- **Daily inventory / Buy Box percentage** for B0D41ZMDPD.\n- **Organic / total sales (purchased-product report)** — to confirm whether the decline is real or just ad-attribution shift.\n- **Competitor ASIN price trend and rating changes** in the T1 MAX solder category.\n- **Xnurta AI target-ACOS change log** per campaign.\n- **Impression / click trend per day** (we have only ad-sales daily, not impressions daily for this ASIN) — would confirm whether ad impression share dropped in mid-April.\n- **Review count and star rating** per day / week.\n- **Prior 90-day history** — to calibrate whether \"declining from $168/day\" is actually a revert-to-mean or a true problem.\n"
