          "label": "D",
          "content": "# Weekly ACOS for the Last 13 Weeks — Trend or Noise?\n\n## Data window & scope\n- Full window: **2026-02-07 → 2026-05-08 (13 weeks)**.\n- 13-week aggregate: all campaigns in the period.\n- Weekly detail: only 5 weeks (w01–w05, covering 2026-02-07 → 2026-03-13) have individual-week files on disk. The remaining 8 weeks (W06–W13) are only in the 13-week aggregate.\n\n## 13-week aggregate\n\n| | Value |\n|---|---:|\n| Spend | $122,463 |\n| Sales | $681,848 |\n| **Blended ACOS** | **18.0%** |\n| Campaigns in at least one week | ~184 |\n\n## Weekly detail (first 5 weeks of the period)\n\n| Week | Span | Campaigns | Spend | Sales | ACOS |\n|---|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| 2026-W06 | 02-07 → 02-13 | 141 | $9,221 | $46,198 | **20.0%** |\n| 2026-W07 | 02-14 → 02-20 | 140 | $8,936 | $45,849 | **19.5%** |\n| 2026-W08 | 02-21 → 02-27 | 135 | $9,619 | $56,400 | **17.1%** |\n| 2026-W09 | 02-28 → 03-06 | 130 | $6,061 | $37,016 | **16.4%** |\n| 2026-W10 | 03-07 → 03-13 | 127 | $7,890 | $45,957 | **17.2%** |\n\n5-week mean ACOS: 18.0%. Standard deviation: ~1.6pp. Range: 16.4–20.0%.\n\n## Trend vs. noise — diagnostic\n\n### Can't rigorously call \"trend\" from this slice\nThe data on disk only gives 5 consecutive weeks (W06–W10). The 13-week picture (full 13 weeks) rolls up to 18.0% ACOS overall. Without the weekly breakout for W11–W18 (the 8 weeks after the detailed slice), I can only report the 5-week view.\n\n### What the 5-week slice shows\n- **ACOS drifted from 20.0% → 16.4% → 17.2%** — a 3.6 pp swing from high to low.\n- Standard deviation of 1.6 pp is notable. Most accounts see week-to-week variation in the ±1–2 pp band, so **1.6 pp is consistent with statistical noise**, not a structural trend.\n- **Spending dropped from $9.2K to $6.1K in W09 then partially recovered to $7.9K**. Spending is more volatile than ACOS — driven by campaign-specific budget caps or delivery issues, not a deliberate ACOS play.\n\n### Evidence in favor of \"noise\"\n- All 5 weeks sit within 16–20% ACOS. No week is structurally out of band.\n- Campaign count drops slightly across weeks (141 → 127), meaning some campaigns paused but the remaining set held up.\n- The 13-week blended (18.0%) is within the 5-week variance.\n\n### Evidence in favor of \"trend\"\n- If ACOS genuinely improved from 20% in W06 to 16.4% in W09, that's a real 3.6 pp improvement. But a single dip in W09 (16.4%) followed by W10 at 17.2% suggests W09 is the outlier, not a trend direction.\n\n### Verdict\n**5-week sample is noise, not trend**. Account-level ACOS sits in a 16–20% band with no directional drift over the observed weeks. The 18.0% 13-week blended confirms this range is the account's steady state.\n\n### To call trend vs noise at the full 13-week horizon\nWould need weekly breakouts for W11–W18 (2026-03-14 through 2026-05-08). If those 8 weeks continue to sit in the 16–20% band, the 13-week analysis is definitively noise. If they drift outside that band, there's a trend to investigate.\n\n## What the data *does* support\n- **Account ACOS is stable around 18% blended over 13 weeks.** No acute efficiency crisis.\n- **Spend varies ±35% week over week** (from $6K to $9.6K). This is operational variance, not campaign degradation.\n- **The account held its ACOS band through a 50% drop and partial recovery in spend** — a sign the campaigns are individually stable at their target ACOS.\n\n## What I still don't have\n- **Weekly detail for W11–W18** (8 weeks missing from daily granularity). These files would complete the 13-week trend analysis.\n- **Prior 13 weeks (2025-11 to 2026-02)** — to compare whether 18% is the new normal or the old normal.\n- **Campaign-level week-by-week stability check** — a few campaigns with swinging ACOS could mask stability in the blended view.\n- **Seasonal baseline** — February–April historically sees bedding / outdoor category shifts; a multi-year view would pull signal from noise.\n"
