          "label": "C",
          "content": "# Weekly Spend by Ad Type (SP / SB / SD) — Last 8 Weeks\n\n## Data window & scope\n- Window: **2026-03-14 → 2026-05-08 (8 weeks)**.\n- Rows: 160 campaign records at campaign × date level.\n- Weekly detail available for 4 weeks (W11–W14). 8-week aggregate covers the full span.\n\n## 8-week aggregate\n\n| Ad type | Spend | Share |\n|---|---:|---:|\n| Sponsored Products | **$77,370** | **95.8%** |\n| Sponsored Brands | $3,366 | 4.2% |\n| Sponsored Display | $0 | 0.0% |\n| **Total** | **$80,737** | 100% |\n\n**Sponsored Display is effectively absent from this account.** It's a two-tier mix: SP dominates, SB is a minor supplement.\n\n## Weekly detail (first 4 of 8 weeks)\n\n| Week | Span | SP spend | SB spend | **SP share** |\n|---|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| W11 | 2026-03-14 → 03-20 | $6,307 | $375 | 94.4% |\n| W12 | 2026-03-21 → 03-27 | $6,781 | $348 | 95.1% |\n| W13 | 2026-03-28 → 04-03 | $6,248 | $247 | 96.2% |\n| W14 | 2026-04-04 → 04-10 | $9,030 | $348 | 96.3% |\n\n## Is the mix shifting?\n\n### Week-over-week trend in SP share\n- W11: 94.4% SP\n- W12: 95.1% SP (+0.7 pp)\n- W13: 96.2% SP (+1.1 pp)\n- W14: 96.3% SP (+0.1 pp)\n\n**SP share is creeping upward** — a shift of ~2 pp from 94.4% to 96.3% over 4 weeks. Small in absolute terms but directionally consistent.\n\n### Where the budget is moving\n- **SP spend rose** from $6.3K (W11) to $9.0K (W14) — +43% in 4 weeks.\n- **SB spend dropped** from $375 (W11) to $247 (W13), partial recovery to $348 (W14). Roughly −7% overall.\n- **SD spend is zero** throughout — SD is not being used in this account.\n\n### Direction: toward Sponsored Products, away from Sponsored Brands\n- Total account spend is rising (driven by SP).\n- SB budget is being held flat or slightly reduced.\n- SD is absent and has been.\n\n## Interpretation\n\n### Why SP is taking share\nGiven EV064's finding that SB actually has **better ACOS (10.3%)** than SP (20.0%) on this account, the shift toward SP is counter-intuitive. Several plausible drivers:\n1. **New product launches** — new ASINs typically start on SP before SB; recent launches would naturally tilt SP share upward.\n2. **Xnurta AI default allocation** — the account has many \"Xnurta AI\"-prefixed SP campaigns. AI-driven bidders tend to scale winning SP campaigns aggressively, pulling share from manual SB.\n3. **SB creative approval lag** — SB needs creative review; a backlog on SB creatives in W12–W14 would freeze SB growth while SP scales.\n4. **Seasonality shift**: W14 (2026-04-04 → 04-10) is when outdoor / cooling products typically start spending up. These categories have more SP than SB inventory.\n\n### Why SB isn't growing\nSB has better ACOS but smaller scale. SB growth usually requires:\n- Brand store / A+ content ready (may be missing for smaller brands).\n- Custom image / video creatives (more production effort).\n- Higher minimum bids.\nIf those aren't being prioritized, SB stays flat.\n\n### Why SD isn't being used at all\nThis is a missed opportunity. From EV088, the SD campaigns (where they exist for other brands on a different profile) run at **7.9% ACOS** — the most efficient tier. Not running SD at all on this profile means leaving the most efficient placement untapped.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n1. **Open at least 3 SD campaigns** to capture remarketing and similar-audience traffic at lower CPM. Start with the top 3 ASINs by SP spend. Expected: +$1–2K/mo spend at 10–15% ACOS.\n2. **Budget 10–15% of total ad spend to SB growth**. SB's lower ACOS is free margin expansion; the current 4.2% SB share is below target.\n3. **Audit why SB is decelerating**. Check creative approval queue, brand store completeness, and Xnurta AI's allocation logic.\n4. **Maintain SP as primary channel** — it's the engine and should be, but 96%+ concentration is over-dependent.\n\n## What I still don't have\n- **Weekly detail for W15–W18** (weeks 5–8 of the 8-week window). These would confirm whether the SP-drift trend continued into mid-April–early-May.\n- **Sales by ad type** — spend alone doesn't reveal ROAS shifts. If SP's sales grew proportionally to its spend, the mix shift is neutral on efficiency; if not, it's eroding efficiency.\n- **Campaign-launch timing** — new-ASIN campaigns explain W14's SP surge only if we can match campaign IDs to their creation dates.\n- **SB creative status changes** — to diagnose why SB isn't growing.\n- **Why SD is zero** — account-level choice, technical blocker, or intentional?\n"
