          "label": "A",
          "content": "Based on the provided dataset (aggregated from the top 100 campaigns which represent the vast majority of the account's volume), here is the decomposition of your Account-level ACOS for the last 30 days compared to the prior 30 days.\n\n### 📊 Account-Level Performance Summary\n\n*   **Last 30 Days (L30):**\n    *   **Spend:** $49,756.89\n    *   **Sales:** $259,912.25\n    *   **ACOS:** **19.14%**\n*   **Prior 30 Days (P30):**\n    *   **Spend:** $21,299.05\n    *   **Sales:** $140,953.39\n    *   **ACOS:** **15.11%**\n*   **Period-over-Period Change:**\n    *   **Spend:** +$28,457.84 (+133.6%)\n    *   **Sales:** +$118,958.86 (+84.4%)\n    *   **ACOS:** **+4.03%** (or +403 basis points)\n\n---\n\n### 🧩 Decomposition of the +4.03% ACOS Increase\n\nTo understand exactly what drove the 4.03% increase in ACOS, we can mathematically isolate the changes in spend, sales, and their compositional interaction:\n\n1.  **Spend Effect: +20.19%**\n    *   *What this means:* If your sales had remained completely flat at P30 levels ($140k), the massive 133% increase in spend would have driven your ACOS up by over 20 percentage points.\n2.  **Sales Effect: -6.92%**\n    *   *What this means:* Fortunately, sales did not remain flat. The strong 84% growth in sales helped absorb a large portion of the new spend, pulling the ACOS back down by roughly 6.9 percentage points.\n3.  **Compositional Shift / Interaction: -9.24%**\n    *   *What this means:* This is the combined mathematical effect of both spend and sales scaling simultaneously. Because both grew significantly, the interaction between the two metrics offset the raw spend effect by an additional 9.2 percentage points.\n\n**Formula Check:** `(+20.19%) + (-6.92%) + (-9.24%) = +4.03% Total ACOS Change`\n\n---\n\n### 🎯 Single Biggest Contributor to the ACOS Increase\n\nThe single biggest drag on the account's ACOS was the **`Hornady-RAPiD_Gun_Safes-MULTI-NB-SP-Phrase`** campaign. \n\nWhile it wasn't the largest campaign by total spend, it was the most highly inefficient driver of *new* spend:\n*   **L30 Performance:** $1,658.40 Spend | $1,530.22 Sales (**108.4% ACOS**)\n*   **P30 Performance:** $236.21 Spend | $916.47 Sales (**25.8% ACOS**)\n*   **The Impact:** This campaign increased its spend by ~$1,422 but only yielded ~$614 in additional sales. This means the *marginal ACOS* on the new spend was a highly inefficient **231%**. \n*   **Account Drag:** If this campaign's performance had remained flat period-over-period, your account-level ACOS would be **50 basis points (0.50%) lower**. \n\n**Notable Runner-Up (The Volume Driver):**\nIt is also worth noting the **`GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad-MULTI-NB-SP-Exact`** campaign. It added a massive **$6,775 in new spend** and **$30,118 in new sales**. Because its marginal ACOS on that new volume was ~22.5% (which is higher than the P30 account average of 15.1%), the sheer weight of this campaign's scale pulled the overall account average up by **44 basis points (0.44%)**."
