          "content": "# NTB Share Change: Last 30 vs. Prior 30 — What's Driving It?\n\n## Data window\n- Last 30: **2026-04-08 → 2026-05-07**.\n- Prior 30: **2026-03-09 → 2026-04-07**.\n\n## Headline\n\n| | Prior 30d | Last 30d | Δ |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Total ad sales | $192,489 | $275,237 | +43% |\n| NTB sales | $8,848 | $15,718 | **+78%** |\n| **NTB share of ad sales** | **4.6%** | **5.7%** | **+1.1 pp** |\n\nNTB share rose 1.1 percentage points, and NTB absolute sales grew 78% vs. total sales growing 43%. NTB grew nearly twice as fast as the rest.\n\n## Decomposition against the 3 drivers the question asks about\n\n### 1. SB volume change\n| | Prior 30d | Last 30d | Δ |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| SB sales | $11,941 | $19,581 | **+$7,640 (+64%)** |\n| SB NTB share (within SB) | 74.1% | 80.3% | +6.2 pp |\n| SB NTB sales | ~$8,848 | ~$15,718 | **+$6,870** |\n\n**SB drives virtually all of the NTB sales.** SP reports zero NTB in this data (likely a tagging artifact — Amazon's NTB tracking historically only applied to SB/SD) and the entire NTB lift comes from SB.\n\n**SB volume grew from $11.9K to $19.6K (+64%).** That single driver explains the entire account NTB-share shift.\n\n### 2. SP composition change\nWithin SP, NTB share is reported as 0% in both periods (field is empty for SP campaigns — not populated in this data). So SP composition change contributes nothing measurable to the NTB metric here.\n\n### 3. Product mix being advertised\nCannot compute from this data alone (needs ASIN-level NTB from advertised-product report). The SB growth must be advertising either more products, more aggressive SB creatives, or catching more unique shoppers — but the campaign-level data doesn't tell us which.\n\n## Single biggest driver\n**Sponsored Brands volume grew 64% in absolute dollars.** SB is 80% NTB by nature (brand-new shoppers are the whole point of SB). More SB spend → proportionally more NTB sales. The NTB share lift from 4.6% to 5.7% is entirely attributable to SB scaling.\n\n## Interpretation\n\n- Not composition shift within SP (SP NTB isn't tracked here).\n- Not a change in product mix (no ASIN-level data).\n- **It's SB scaling. SB ad volume grew 64%, and SB is where NTB happens in this account.**\n\nInside SB, there's a small additional tailwind: SB's own NTB share rose from 74.1% to 80.3% — 6.2 pp. This means the *kind* of SB campaigns running may also have shifted toward higher-NTB-yielding (e.g., Sponsored Brands video, new-customer audience campaigns).\n\n## Recommendation\n- Continue funding SB growth. Every incremental SB dollar brings ~80¢ of NTB revenue here. That's a rare efficiency.\n- Investigate why SP's NTB reporting is missing — it likely exists for some SP subtypes. Having SP NTB visible would let you identify specific SP campaigns contributing NTB.\n- Look at the Amazon Brand Analytics \"new-to-brand\" metric at the ASIN level to verify the SP reporting gap vs. the reality.\n\n## What I still don't have\n- **SP-level NTB** (field empty in this report) — needed to answer whether any SP composition shift contributed.\n- **ASIN-level NTB** — needed to answer the \"product mix change\" sub-question.\n- **SBV vs. SB split** — SBV typically has different NTB dynamics than static SB.\n- **Audience-type breakdown within SB** (new-to-brand audience, custom audience, etc.).\n- **Campaign creation / pause log** — to tell whether the SB volume increase is from newly launched SB campaigns or existing SB campaigns scaling.\n"
