          "content": "# ROAS Change by Ad Type — Last 30 vs. Prior 30\n\n## Data window\n- Last 30: 2025-04-09 → 2025-05-08.\n- Prior 30: 2025-03-10 → 2025-04-08.\n- **Data coverage caveat**: the report-last-30 and report-prior-30 files only contain SP and SB rows. SD is not in this dataset (likely filtered out or zero activity in this account for SD in both periods).\n\n## Headline\n\n| Ad type | Prior ROAS | Last ROAS | ΔROAS | Δ spend | Δ sales |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| Sponsored Products | **6.63** | **5.50** | **−1.13** | −$8,022 | **−$117,363** |\n| Sponsored Brands | **4.64** | **8.38** | **+3.73** | −$1,483 | −$4,506 |\n\n## Largest ROAS change: Sponsored Brands\n\nDespite SB's absolute dollar scale being ~1% of the account, SB had the largest **ROAS movement**: from 4.64× to 8.38× (+3.73). SB's ROAS nearly doubled.\n\nDecomposition of the SB change:\n\n- **Spend fell $1,483** (from $2,121 to $637, -70%).\n- **Sales fell $4,506** (from $9,847 to $5,340, -46%).\n\nSpend fell faster than sales → ROAS improved. SB scaled back, but the surviving campaigns were more efficient. The winners in SB kept converting; the losers were paused. Classic \"right-size the channel\" story.\n\n## Sponsored Products decomposition\n\nSP's ROAS dropped from 6.63× to 5.50× (−1.13).\n- **Spend fell $8,022** (from $64,651 to $56,630, -12%).\n- **Sales fell $117,363** (from $428,557 to $311,194, -27%).\n\nSales fell **more than 2× faster** than spend → ROAS degraded. The spending pulled back, but the sales fell disproportionately. This is typical when category demand contracts or listing efficiency weakens while bidding stays roughly stable.\n\n## Which change is \"biggest\"?\n- By **ΔROAS magnitude**: SB (+3.73 vs SP -1.13).\n- By **dollar impact**: SP (−$117K in sales vs SB −$4.5K).\n\n## Interpretation\n- **SB's ROAS improvement is real but irrelevant to the account dollar bottom line** — SB only moves about $5–10K of sales.\n- **SP's ROAS degradation, while smaller in magnitude, moves 100× more dollars**. The account lost $117K of ad-attributed sales to a 12% spend reduction and a 27% sales contraction. The actual business question is on SP: why did SP sales fall 27% while spend only pulled back 12%? Probably listing / inventory / category-demand shift, not advertising configuration.\n\n## Recommendations\n1. **SB**: whatever pruning happened in the SB set was right. Don't reverse. Consider lifting SB budget on the surviving campaigns to recapture the 70% spend cut at the new 8.38× ROAS.\n2. **SP**: the −$117K sales drop at −$8K spend is a red flag. Look at campaign-level breakdowns (see EV167 and EV086 for related analyses). Most likely culprits: a few large campaigns had listing issues or ASIN stockouts, dragging the whole SP ROAS down.\n3. **SD**: not present in this data. If SD is being run at all in this account, re-pull it and include in the 3-way comparison. If SD truly is zero, that's a missed efficiency (see EV163 on the same pattern).\n\n## What I still don't have\n- **SD data** for either period.\n- **Campaign-level decomposition** inside SP — to pinpoint which campaigns lost the $117K of sales.\n- **ASIN-level sales** to separate listing-side from advertising-side changes.\n- **Organic sales** — to confirm whether the SP sales drop reflects total business contraction or is shuffling to organic.\n- **SB campaign list before and after the prune** — to know exactly which SB campaigns were paused.\n"
