          "label": "D",
          "content": "> **Note on date ranges assumed:** Last 30 days = 2026-04-09 ~ 2026-05-08; Prior 30 days = 2026-03-10 ~ 2026-04-08. ROAS change is computed as (ROAS_last30 − ROAS_prior30) / ROAS_prior30 × 100%. The decomposition isolates how much of the ROAS shift is driven by spend changes vs. sales changes. Please let me know if you'd like to adjust any of these parameters.\n\n> **Note on SD data:** No SD (Sponsored Display) campaign data was returned for either period under this profile. The analysis below covers SP and SB only.\n\n---\n\n## 🔑 Key Findings\n\n1. **SP had the largest ROAS change** — dropping **−20.4%** (from 6.28 → 5.00), making it the most impacted ad type by far.\n2. **SB moved in the opposite direction** — ROAS improved **+11.9%** (from 8.20 → 9.17).\n3. **Spend surge is the primary culprit for SP's ROAS decline** — SP spend nearly doubled (+82.7%), which mechanically diluted ROAS by −4.14 points; this was only partially offset by a +2.86 point lift from higher sales.\n4. **SB's ROAS gain was sales-driven** — SB sales grew faster (+63.5%) than spend (+46.2%), generating a +5.21 point sales effect that more than offset the −4.23 point drag from higher spend.\n\n---\n\n## ROAS Change Decomposition by Ad Type\n\n\n| Ad Type | Spend Prior 30 (USD) | Spend Last 30 (USD) | Spend Δ % | Sales Prior 30 (USD) | Sales Last 30 (USD) | Sales Δ % | ROAS Prior 30 | ROAS Last 30 | ROAS Δ (abs) | ROAS Δ % | Spend Effect on ROAS | Sales Effect on ROAS |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Sponsored Products | 28869.3 | 52755.05 | 82.74 | 181439.53 | 263938.53 | 45.47 | 6.28 | 5 | -1.28 | -20.39 | -4.14 | 2.86 |\n| Sponsored Brands | 1459.06 | 2132.75 | 46.17 | 11958.61 | 19558.28 | 63.55 | 8.2 | 9.17 | 0.97 | 11.89 | -4.23 | 5.21 |\n\n---\n\n## Analysis\n\n\n### Sponsored Products (SP) — Largest ROAS Decline: −20.4%\n\n| Metric | Prior 30 | Last 30 | Change |\n|--------|----------|---------|--------|\n| Spend (USD) | $28,869 | $52,755 | **+82.7%** |\n| Sales (USD) | $181,440 | $263,939 | +45.5% |\n| ROAS | 6.28 | 5.00 | **−1.28 (−20.4%)** |\n\n**Decomposition:**\n- **Spend Effect: −4.14** — Spend grew nearly twice as fast as sales. Holding sales constant at the last-30 level, the spend increase alone would have reduced ROAS by 4.14 points.\n- **Sales Effect: +2.86** — Sales did grow substantially (+$82.5K), which partially recovered ROAS by 2.86 points.\n- **Net:** The spend surge overwhelmed the sales gain, resulting in a net ROAS decline of −1.28.\n\n> **Interpretation:** SP is scaling aggressively — spend is up 83% while sales are up only 45%. This suggests either the incremental spend is going into less efficient placements/targets, or the account is in an expansion phase accepting higher ACOS to capture volume.\n\n---\n\n### Sponsored Brands (SB) — ROAS Improvement: +11.9%\n\n| Metric | Prior 30 | Last 30 | Change |\n|--------|----------|---------|--------|\n| Spend (USD) | $1,459 | $2,133 | **+46.2%** |\n| Sales (USD) | $11,959 | $19,558 | +63.5% |\n| ROAS | 8.20 | 9.17 | **+0.97 (+11.9%)** |\n\n**Decomposition:**\n- **Spend Effect: −4.23** — Even SB's spend increase created downward pressure on ROAS (−4.23 points) in isolation.\n- **Sales Effect: +5.21** — However, sales grew faster than spend, contributing a +5.21 point lift that more than compensated.\n- **Net:** Sales growth outpaced spend growth, yielding a net ROAS improvement of +0.97.\n\n> **Interpretation:** SB is scaling efficiently — every additional dollar of spend is generating more than proportional sales. This is a healthy scaling pattern.\n\n---\n\n### SD (Sponsored Display) — No Data\n\nNo SD campaign data was found for this profile in either period. If SD campaigns exist, they may not have been active or may have had zero spend/sales during these windows."
