          "label": "B",
          "content": "> **A note on methodology:** Since no time range was specified, I analyzed two consecutive 7-day periods — **current: May 2–8, 2026** and **prior: Apr 25–May 1, 2026**. Hero ASINs are defined as the **top 10 ASINs by spend in the current period**; all remaining ASINs are Long Tail. ACOS movement is decomposed using a spend-weighted method: each segment's contribution = its current-period spend share × its ACOS change. Please let me know if you'd like to adjust any of these assumptions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔑 Key Findings\n\n1. **The Long Tail is the primary culprit.** Account ACOS rose +1.01 pp overall, and the Long Tail segment contributed **+1.86 pp** — nearly double the total movement — while Hero ASINs partially offset it with **−0.64 pp**.\n2. **Hero ASINs actually improved.** Their weighted ACOS fell from 21.0% → 19.8% (−1.22 pp), a healthy sign for the account's largest spend block.\n3. **Long Tail ACOS deteriorated sharply.** It jumped from 18.9% → 22.8% (+3.90 pp), driven in part by a significant spend increase (+$1,495, up ~36%) flowing into less efficient ASINs.\n4. **Within Hero ASINs, performance is mixed** — a few individual ASINs (notably B081DK7DQH +9.4 pp, B07XDBD4C4 +5.3 pp) worsened, but these were outweighed by strong improvements elsewhere (B01F209RSI −84 pp, B008SPG6GHF −8.4 pp).\n\n---\n\n## 1. Account-Level ACOS Movement\n\n\n| Current ACOS % (May 2–8) | Prior ACOS % (Apr 25–May 1) | ACOS Change (pp) |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 21.1 | 20.08 | 1.01 |\n\nThe account ACOS increased by **+1.01 percentage points** week-over-week.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Segment Contribution Breakdown\n\n\n| Segment | Current Spend (USD) | Current Sales (USD) | Current ACOS % | Prior Spend (USD) | Prior Sales (USD) | Prior ACOS % | ACOS Change (pp) | Current Spend Share % | Contribution to ACOS Movement (pp) |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Hero | 6208.76 | 31432.72 | 19.75 | 6238.16 | 29744.83 | 20.97 | -1.22 | 52.16 | -0.64 |\n| Long Tail | 5695.43 | 24987.46 | 22.79 | 4200.09 | 22226.34 | 18.9 | 3.9 | 47.84 | 1.86 |\n\n**How to read the contribution column:** Contribution = Current Spend Share × ACOS Change. It answers: \"If only this segment had changed, how much would account ACOS have moved?\"\n\n| Segment | Direction | Magnitude |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Long Tail** | ↑ Worsened | **+1.86 pp** — the dominant driver |\n| **Hero ASINs** | ↓ Improved | **−0.64 pp** — a partial offset |\n| **Net Account** | ↑ | **+1.01 pp** |\n\nThe Long Tail's contribution (+1.86 pp) **exceeds the total account movement (+1.01 pp)**, meaning Hero ASINs were actively pulling ACOS down but couldn't fully counteract the Long Tail drag.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Hero ASIN Detail (Top 10 by Current Spend)\n\n\n| ASIN | Current Spend (USD) | Current ACOS % | Prior Spend (USD) | Prior ACOS % | ACOS Change (pp) |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B081DK7DQH\">B081DK7DQH</Link> | 514.1 | 32.55 | 597.02 | 23.17 | 9.38 |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B07XDBD4C4\">B07XDBD4C4</Link> | 1386.51 | 36.25 | 1597.26 | 30.98 | 5.27 |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B07XKW55KJ\">B07XKW55KJ</Link> | 708.82 | 21.42 | 658.91 | 18.36 | 3.06 |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B006NONHNE\">B006NONHNE</Link> | 1206.29 | 11.91 | 1181.18 | 12.41 | -0.5 |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B000PD6QJ6\">B000PD6QJ6</Link> | 359.9 | 17.01 | 317.49 | 19.97 | -2.96 |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B006NOO440\">B006NOO440</Link> | 310.07 | 15.99 | 317.96 | 20.37 | -4.38 |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B081DJPYM8\">B081DJPYM8</Link> | 441.22 | 14.21 | 511.54 | 21.24 | -7.03 |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B007JT4P88\">B007JT4P88</Link> | 652.71 | 24.12 | 601.53 | 32.14 | -8.02 |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B08SPG6GHF\">B08SPG6GHF</Link> | 355.87 | 15.47 | 331.38 | 23.88 | -8.41 |\n| <Link entity=\"asin\" name=\"B01F209RSI\">B01F209RSI</Link> | 273.27 | 64.28 | 123.89 | 148.35 | -84.07 |\n\n**Notable observations within Hero ASINs:**\n- **B081DK7DQH** (+9.38 pp) and **B07XDBD4C4** (+5.27 pp) are the two Hero ASINs with meaningful ACOS deterioration — worth monitoring.\n- **B01F209RSI** showed a dramatic improvement (−84 pp), though its prior ACOS of 148% suggests it was previously highly inefficient; the current 64% ACOS is still elevated.\n- **B007JT4P88**, **B081DJPYM8**, and **B08SPG6GHF** all improved by 7–8 pp, contributing to the Hero segment's overall ACOS improvement.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Diagnosis: Why Is the Long Tail Driving ACOS Up?\n\n\nTwo forces are at work in the Long Tail:\n\n1. **ACOS efficiency declined** (+3.90 pp): Long Tail ASINs converted spend into sales less efficiently this week — their collective ACOS rose from 18.9% to 22.8%.\n\n2. **Spend expanded significantly** (+$1,495, ~+36%): More budget flowed into Long Tail ASINs this period (from $4,200 to $5,695). When spend grows faster than sales efficiency can support, the segment's drag on account ACOS amplifies. The Long Tail now accounts for **47.8% of total spend**, up from a lower base in the prior period.\n\nTogether, these two factors — worse efficiency *and* higher spend share — make the Long Tail the clear primary driver of the account's ACOS increase this week.\n\nHero ASINs, by contrast, maintained spend stability (~$6,209 vs $6,238) while improving their weighted ACOS, suggesting the core portfolio is performing well."
