          "label": "C",
          "content": "> **Inference note:** The analysis covers **April 9 – May 8, 2026 (last 30 days)**. The TACOS decomposition framework used is: **Total Sales = Ad-Attributed Sales (Same SKU) + Halo Sales (Other SKU) + Implied Organic Baseline**, where TACOS = Ad Spend ÷ Total Sales. Total Sales is sourced from ASIN-level data (`TotalSalesAmount`), and ad-attributed components are sourced from product ad metrics. If this time range or methodology doesn't match your intent, please let me know.\n\n---\n\n## 🔑 Key Findings\n\n1. **Organic dominates the revenue mix** — 81.3% of total sales ($1.41M) came from non-ad organic sources, indicating a strong organic foundation that advertising is built on top of.\n2. **Halo sales outpace same-SKU ad sales** — Halo (Other SKU) sales ($155K, 11.0%) exceeded same-SKU ad-attributed sales ($108K, 7.7%), suggesting ads are driving meaningful cross-product discovery and lift.\n3. **TACOS is highly efficient at 3.73%** — With only $52.7K in spend against $1.41M in total sales, the account is running a lean ad investment relative to total revenue.\n4. **ACOS vs. TACOS gap is wide (20.0% vs. 3.73%)** — This 5.4× spread confirms that the majority of sales are not directly attributed to ads, reinforcing the organic baseline's dominance.\n\n---\n\n## Account-Level TACOS Decomposition Brief\n### Period: April 9 – May 8, 2026 (Last 30 Days)\n\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Ad Spend (USD) | Total Sales (USD) | Ad-Attributed Sales / Same SKU (USD) | Ad-Attributed Share (%) | Halo Sales / Other SKU (USD) | Halo Sales Share (%) | Implied Organic Baseline (USD) | Organic Baseline Share (%) | TACOS (%) | ACOS (%) |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| 52722.31 | 1414529.53 | 108464.05 | 7.67 | 155452.49 | 10.99 | 1150612.99 | 81.34 | 3.73 | 19.98 |\n\n---\n\n### Sales Component Breakdown\n\n| Sales Bucket | Sales Amount (USD) | Share of Total Sales (%) |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Implied Organic Baseline | 1150612.99 | 81.34 |\n| Halo Sales (Other SKU) | 155452.49 | 10.99 |\n| Ad-Attributed Sales (Same SKU) | 108464.05 | 7.67 |\n\n---\n\n## Decomposition Narrative\n\n### 1. Total Sales Baseline\nTotal account sales for the period were **$1,414,529.53 (USD)**, sourced entirely from Seller-side `TotalSalesAmount` (Vendor `ShippedRevenue` = $0, confirming this is a Seller-only account).\n\n### 2. The Three Buckets\n\n| Bucket | Amount (USD) | Share | Definition |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Ad-Attributed Sales (Same SKU)** | $108,464 | **7.7%** | Sales of the exact promoted product, directly attributed to ad clicks |\n| **Halo Sales (Other SKU)** | $155,452 | **11.0%** | Sales of *other* products in the catalog attributed to the same ad click — cross-sell / brand halo effect |\n| **Implied Organic Baseline** | $1,150,613 | **81.3%** | Total sales not attributable to any ad click — organic search, direct, repeat purchase, etc. |\n\n> ✅ **Cross-check passed:** The implied organic baseline ($1,150,612.99) reconciles almost exactly with the ASIN-level `OrganicSales` field ($1,150,640.96), a difference of only **$27.97** (~0.002%). This confirms the decomposition is internally consistent.\n\n### 3. Efficiency Metrics\n\n| Metric | Value | Interpretation |\n|---|---|---|\n| **TACOS** | **3.73%** | Ad spend as % of *total* account sales — very lean |\n| **ACOS** | **20.0%** | Ad spend as % of *ad-attributed* sales only — within typical healthy range |\n| **Ad Sales Share** (Same SKU + Halo) | **18.7%** | Combined ad-influenced revenue as % of total sales |\n| **Organic Leverage Ratio** | ~4.4× | For every $1 of ad-attributed sales, ~$4.4 of organic sales is generated |\n\n### 4. Structural Observations\n\n- **The organic engine is the primary revenue driver.** 81.3% of sales require no ad spend to generate, which means the account has strong brand equity, organic ranking, or repeat-purchase behavior that advertising is supplementing rather than replacing.\n- **Halo effect is significant and exceeds same-SKU ad returns.** Other-SKU halo sales ($155K) are 43% larger than same-SKU ad sales ($108K). This suggests ads are effectively introducing shoppers to the broader catalog — a pattern common in accounts with complementary product lines or strong brand stores.\n- **TACOS at 3.73% is well below typical thresholds** (often 8–15% for growth-stage accounts), indicating either a mature, organically strong account or one that is under-investing in ads relative to its sales potential. Whether this is optimal depends on the growth objective."
