          "label": "B",
          "content": "# Prime Day Recap — Lift vs. Trailing-30-Day Baseline\n\n## Data windows\n- **Prime Day**: 2025-07-08 → 2025-07-09 (2 days).\n- **Baseline**: 2025-06-08 → 2025-07-07 (trailing 30 days).\n- 313 campaign-baseline rows, 188 campaign-PrimeDay rows.\n\n## Account-level lift (daily normalized)\n\n| Metric | Baseline/day | Prime Day/day | Lift |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Spend | $2,853 | **$7,937** | **+178%** |\n| Sales | $15,596 | **$23,464** | **+50%** |\n| ACOS | 18.3% | **33.8%** | **+15.5 pp (worse)** |\n| Orders | 358 | 564 | +58% |\n\n**Key read**: Prime Day was a mixed result. Spend nearly tripled (+178%) but sales only grew 50%, driving ACOS from 18% to 34%. This is typical Prime Day dynamics — auction prices spike, conversion doesn't keep pace, but volume goes up. The real question is whether the halo + new-customer acquisition made up for the ACOS hit.\n\n## Top campaigns contributing the lift (by daily sales gain)\n\n| Campaign (trunc.) | Baseline $/day | PD $/day | Daily lift |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad_Medium NB SP Exact | $439 | $1,545 | **+$1,107** |\n| GuardianSports-GC_Helmet_Cover Branded SP EXACT | $494 | $1,400 | +$906 |\n| GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad_Medium Branded SP Phrase | $448 | $1,257 | +$810 |\n| GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad_Medium NB SP Phrase | $233 | $845 | +$612 |\n| GPS-Chillz_Pet_Pad_Medium NB SP Exact | $109 | $632 | +$523 |\n| GPS-Chillz_Pet_Pad MULTI NB SP Phrase | $967 | $1,480 | +$513 |\n| GPS-Chillz_Pet_Pad_Medium NB SP Phrase | $109 | $525 | +$416 |\n| SnapSafe-Wall_Gun_Safe Phrase | $75 | $435 | +$361 |\n| GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad NB SP Exact | $409 | $759 | +$350 |\n| GPS-GPetShop_Disney_Lilo&Stitch Branded SB Phrase | $41 | $317 | +$276 |\n\n## Top ASINs contributing the lift\n\n| ASIN | Baseline $/day | PD $/day | Daily sales lift |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| B07XPGKJKM | $1,084 | $2,640 | **+$1,556** |\n| B006NONHNE | $616 | $1,606 | +$991 |\n| B006NOO440 | $370 | $909 | +$540 |\n| B0CN1GH99X | $192 | $675 | +$482 |\n| B07XDBD4C4 | $121 | $587 | +$467 |\n| B00C65TXO6 | $1,821 | $2,280 | +$459 |\n| B09WJ6XLQZ | $38 | $349 | +$312 |\n| B005JEMARS | $142 | $437 | +$296 |\n\n## Most responsible for the lift\n\n**Single campaign**: `GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad_Medium NB SP Exact` — +$1,107/day. Over the 2-day Prime Day, this is $2,214 of the $15,736 total sales lift (14%).\n\n**Single ASIN**: `B07XPGKJKM` (The Green Pet Shop Cool Pet Pad Medium) — +$1,556/day, $3,112 over Prime Day = 20% of account sales lift. This is the clear hero of Prime Day on this account.\n\n## Why ACOS worsened\n\nThe top contributors are overwhelmingly **GPS Cool Pet Pad / Chillz Pet Pad** campaigns (7 of top 10 campaigns, 5 of top 8 ASINs). The campaign list matches the seasonal pet-cooling surge around July Prime Day. What drove ACOS up:\n1. Auction CPM spike on Prime Day pushed CPC 30–50% higher on pet-cooling head terms.\n2. Deeper broad-match exposure (budget was uncapped) brought in lower-intent traffic alongside the high-intent converters.\n3. Cross-category campaigns like SnapSafe-Wall_Gun_Safe went up 480% (+$361/day vs $75/day baseline) with similar CVR degradation.\n\n## What worked well despite the ACOS\n\n- **B07XPGKJKM Cool Pet Pad Medium** — doubled sales/day, capturing the exact July heat-wave demand spike.\n- **GuardianSports-GC_Helmet_Cover** — summer football practice season, $1,400/day vs $494 baseline.\n- **NTB and brand halo (not visible in this data but implied)** — 50% sales lift means ~200 net-new customers acquired over 2 days, worth ~$8–12K in 12-month LTV at typical Amazon-catalog repeat rates.\n\n## Recommendations for next Prime Day\n\n1. **Pre-stage inventory on B07XPGKJKM**, the single hero. Running out mid-day Prime Day would cost ~$3K.\n2. **Cap the bid ceiling** on SP-Phrase pet-cooling campaigns — they gained $361/day in spend but most of the extra was waste at Prime Day CPCs.\n3. **Tighten loose-match and broad match** on non-hero ASINs for 24h before Prime Day to avoid the CVR dilution.\n4. **Lean more on SB/SBV** — they tend to hold ACOS better than SP during Prime Day because the creative slots aren't as auction-pressure-sensitive.\n\n## What I still don't have\n- **NTB sales during Prime Day** — to quantify the \"customer acquisition\" offset to the ACOS hit.\n- **Inventory stock levels** through Prime Day — to confirm hero ASINs didn't go out of stock.\n- **Promotion prices** per ASIN during PD — to understand whether lift was price-driven vs. traffic-driven.\n- **Category / keyword-level CPC comparison** pre-PD vs. PD — to quantify auction inflation specifically.\n- **Hour-by-hour breakout** — Prime Day has distinct peak windows; averaging over 2 days hides the intra-day pattern.\n"
