          "label": "B",
          "content": "# Ad Spend Distribution Across ASINs — vs. Sales Distribution\n\n## Data window\n- Window: **2026-04-09 → 2026-05-08 (30 days)**.\n- Ad spend: $52,600 (allocated to ASINs by their share of campaign sales).\n- Ad sales: $276,600 across 314 unique ASINs.\n\n## Spend concentration\n\n| Cohort | Share of spend |\n|---|---:|\n| Top 5 ASINs | **25.4%** ($13,347) |\n| Top 10 ASINs | **41.1%** ($21,625) |\n| Top 25 ASINs | **63.2%** ($33,256) |\n| All other ASINs (~289) | **36.8%** ($19,345) |\n\n## Sales distribution\n\n| Cohort | Share of sales |\n|---|---:|\n| Top 5 by sales | 25.9% |\n| Top 10 by sales | 43.3% |\n| Top 25 by sales | 65.4% |\n| Rest | 34.6% |\n\n## Same-cohort comparison (top-N-by-spend vs their sales share)\n\n| Cohort | Spend share | Sales share | Ratio |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Top 5 by spend | 25.4% | 23.4% | **0.92** (slightly under-earning) |\n| Top 10 by spend | 41.1% | 43.3% | 1.05 (earning in proportion) |\n| Top 25 by spend | 63.2% | 63.0% | 1.00 (proportionally) |\n\n## Is the account spending in proportion to where it's earning?\n\n**Yes, approximately**. The match is close:\n- Top 5 by spend: 25% of spend → 23% of sales. A **slight over-spend** on the top 5 (they earn 2 pp less than their spend share).\n- Top 10: 41% spend → 43% sales. **Balanced** — slight under-spend relative to sales.\n- Top 25: 63% / 63%. Perfectly proportional.\n\nThe long tail (the remaining ~289 ASINs) gets 36.8% of spend for 37% of sales — also proportional.\n\n## Signal interpretation\n\n| Signal | Assessment |\n|---|---|\n| Balanced top-25 (63/63) | Healthy spend allocation; no major misalignment |\n| Slight Top-5 over-spend (25.4 → 23.4) | Worth investigating **which of the top 5 is the \"lagging earner\"** — it may indicate one ASIN's efficiency degrading |\n| Long tail balanced (37/37) | Auto-targeting and broad-match campaigns are generally doing their job |\n\n## The \"under-earning\" in the top 5 — who's responsible?\n\nLooking at top-5-by-spend vs their sales (individual ASINs):\n\n| Rank (by spend) | ASIN | Spend share | Sales share | Spend − Sales (pp) |\n|---:|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| 1 | B006NONHNE | 6.3% | 7.2% | −0.9 (earning more than its spend share) |\n| 2 | B081DK7DQH | 6.0% | 2.4% | **+3.6** (under-earning) |\n| 3 | B09TQ2CW9L | 5.5% | 3.9% | +1.6 (under-earning) |\n| 4 | B0C5MYTF7W | 4.8% | 5.5% | −0.7 |\n| 5 | B006NOO440 | 3.7% | 4.5% | −0.8 |\n\n**B081DK7DQH is the single ASIN over-spending relative to its earnings.** Its ACOS from EV180 is **48%** (vs account blended ~19%). This is consistent with EV180's finding — B081DK7DQH is the \"hero ASIN with a problem\".\n\n## Recommendation\n\n1. **Top-5 allocation is close to balanced**, so no blanket \"rebalance top 5\" action is needed.\n2. **B081DK7DQH specifically is over-allocated** — fix this ASIN's ad efficiency (48% ACOS is high) rather than simply redistribute its spend.\n3. **Long tail is well-served** — auto-targeting / broad-match is capturing proportional sales.\n4. **No urgent reallocation needed at the cohort level**. This account's spend is already pretty proportional to its earnings.\n\n## What I still don't have\n- **Per-ASIN ACOS** stability over time — a single-month snapshot may miss dynamics. Pulling 90-day history would confirm whether B081DK7DQH has always under-earned or if it's a recent drift.\n- **Inventory** on top 5 — a top earner going out of stock mid-month would explain a spend-vs-sales mismatch.\n- **Parent-ASIN aggregation** — some of the top ASINs are children of the same parent; aggregating to parents would give a cleaner concentration view.\n- **Campaign-share per ASIN** — to know whether to fix B081DK7DQH via bid cuts (EV188) or full campaign restructure.\n"
